= importizer
:toc:

Are you looking to convert your header-based C{plus}{plus} codebase to C{plus}{plus}20 modules, but
afraid that modularizing is too cumbersome? *importizer* is here to help.

And by modularization I don’t mean exposing a module interface and wrapping. headers. I mean native
modules a.k.a using modules internally.

*Note:* This project is currently going through a complete rewrite using Clang LibTooling to replace
Regex (pre-2.0.0). Much pre-2.0.0 code are gone, but releases and git history are preserved.

This project uses https://semver.org[semantic versioning].

== Why native C{plus}{plus} modules?

* *Improved compilation time:* Modules don’t need to be recompiled every time it is imported, unlike
headers.
* *Improved encapsulation:* Modules allow you to choose what is exposed to users (exported), no need
to hide stuff with a `detail` namespace. Includes and macros from a module will only stay in that
module.
* https://arewemodulesyet.org

== Prebuilt binaries

Importizer provides pre-compiled binaries for major operating systems. Necessary shared libraries
are bundled directly in the distribution archive.

[%autowidth]
|===
| |Linux |macOS |Windows

|Architecture
3+^.^|x64, arm64

|Minimum OS
|None
|macOS 15{plus}
|Windows 10{plus}

|Format (release)
3+^.^|zst(bin)

|Format (debug)
|tzst(bin {plus} .so)
|tzst(bin {plus} .dylib)
|tzst(bin {plus} .dll)
|===

* *Stable release:* Download optimized release builds from the
https://github.com/msqr1/importizer/releases[releases page].
* *Bleeding edge (debug):* Download unoptimized builds from the
https://github.com/msqr1/importizer/releases/tag/continuous[continuous tag]. Useful for testing
latest features or reporting bugs.

== Configuration & usage

Importizer primarily uses a TOML configuration file, complemented by a few command-line options.

=== Command-line interface (CLI)

By default, running `importizer` looks for an `importizer.toml` file in the current working
directory. You can override this by passing the path as a positional argument: `importizer`
`path/to/config.toml`.

[%autowidth]
|===
|Option |Description

|-h, --help
|Print help information and exit.

|-v, --version
|Print version information and exit.

|-o, --outDir
|Override the output directory specified in the config file.

|-r, --raw
|Disable ANSI styling in logs (`always` or `never`). Defaults to `always` if no value is provided.
Can also be toggled via the `RAW` environment variable.
|===

=== Configuration file (TOML)

All relative paths defined in the configuration file are resolved relative to the configuration
file’s location, *not* the current working directory.

[%autowidth]
|===
|Option |Type |Description

|`inDir`
|String
|*Required.* The directory containing the source code to process.

|`outDir`
|String
|*Required* (unless provided via CLI). The directory for the modularized output.

|`compilationDb`
|String
|*Highly Recommended.* Path to a `compile_commands.json` compilation database to provide context.
|===

==== Bootstrap mode

For projects without a JSON compilation database, Importizer can attempt to imitate one using the
`[bootstrap]` table. Note: If `compilationDb` is specified, the `bootstrap` table is ignored.

[%autowidth]
|===
|Option |Type |Default |Description

|`hdrExts`
|String Array
|`["h","hh","hpp","hxx",""]`
|Header file extensions used in the project.

|`srcExts`
|String Array
|`["cc","cpp","cxx","c{plus}{plus}","C"]`
|Source file extensions used in the project.

|`includePaths`
|String Array
|`[]`
|Include paths to search during resolution.
|===

=== Example config file

[source,toml]
----
inDir = "src"
outDir = "modular_src"
# compilationDb = "build/compile_commands.json"

[bootstrap]
includePaths = ["include", "third_party/libs"]
----

== Developing

=== Environment

==== Terminal environment

*Before doing anything else*, setup the environment (check architecture, compiler, backend & set
environment variables) for a terminal  by running `. scripts/setup-env/{OS}`. Note:

* For Windows, there's an optional argument `llvmPrefix` to change the directory (default is
`C:/Program Files/LLVM`) to look for LLVM. It can take the special value of `:bundled` that tells
the script to look for the LLVM bundled within Visual Studio or Build Tools.

==== Skip building LibTooling

Importizer heavily relies on Clang LibTooling. To save developers from compiling it and speed up CI,
there's prebuilt ones. Because C++ ABIs and LLVM bitcode formats change drastically between
compilers and patch versions:

* **Skip building LibTooling:** If you match the toolchain in the table below (which is used to
build LibTooling for CI), the prebuilt LibTooling will integrate seamlessly. You can start coding
right away. Run `cmake -P scripts/setup-env/{OS}`
* **Building from source entirely:** You are free to use other compiler toolchains (GCC, MSVC,
Apple Clang, another Clang), but you will have to rebuild LibTooling with that toolchain.

[%autowidth]
|===
| |Linux |MacOS |Windows

|Build system
3+^.^|CMake 3.31.5{plus}

|Generator
3+^.^|Ninja

|Compiler
|Clang 18.1.8
|Clang 18.1.8 (Homebrew)
|Clang 20.1.x^1^

|Backend
|`build-essential`
|Xcode SDK (`SDKROOT`)
|Visual Studio or Build Tools^2^
|===

. `20.1.8` on x64, `20.1.6` on ARM64.
. Used strictly to provide the Windows SDK.

=== Dependency linkage

Because Importizer relies heavily on Clang LibTooling and LLVM, the resulting binary linkage varies
by operating system

[%autowidth]
|===
| |Linux |MacOS |Windows

|LibTooling
|Dynamic^1^
2+^.^|Static

|Other 3rd-party
3+^.^|Static

|C++ Standard Library
|Static
.2+^.^|Dynamic^2^
|Static

|C Standard Library
|Dynamic^3^
|Dynamic^4^
|===

. Package manager doesn’t offer static build, pending self-built LLVM.
. Dynamic with stable ABI
guaranteed by macOS (libSystem), we can treat as if static.
. Dynamic glibc, pending switch to a
static C Standard Library (musl, LLVM libc).
. Dynamic with stable ABI guaranteed by Windows (UCRT),
we can treat as if static.

=== Building from source

Standard CMake build process. To clone and build the release executable:

[source,bash]
----
git clone --depth 1 https://github.com/msqr1/importizer cd importizer

# Configure the project cmake -B build -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release

# Build using all available cores cmake --build build --config Release -j $(cmake -P
scripts/Nproc.cmake)
----

* The compiled executable will be located in the `build` directory

=== Running tests

Tests are not enabled by default, but can be toggled via the `BUILD_TESTING` CMake option.

[source,bash]
----
# Ensure tests are configured (Debug mode recommended for testing) cmake -B build
-DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Debug -DBUILD_TESTING=ON cmake --build build --config Debug -j $(cmake -P
scripts/Nproc.cmake)

# Run the test suite using all available cores ctest --test-dir build/tests --output-on-failure
--progress --schedule-random -j \ $(cmake -P scripts/Nproc.cmake)
----

=== Adding new tests

Importizer uses a custom directory-based test harness (located in `src/run-test`). To add a new test
case:

. Create a new directory under `tests/` with a descriptive name (e.g., `tests/my-new-feature/`).
. Add a `Config.toml` file inside this directory to configure the importizer run.
. Add a `RefCli.txt` file containing the expected CLI output.
. *(Optional)* Create a `in/` subdirectory containing the input files (C{plus}{plus} header-based
code).
. *(Optional)* Create a `ref/` subdirectory containing the expected output files. The test driver
will automatically compare the actual output directory against this reference directory. Don’t add
this when expecting an error.

The CMake script dynamically globs the `tests/` folder, so your new test will be automatically
picked up on the next `cmake` `-B` `build` run.

=== General rules

* 100-column per line limit for files & CLI outputs

==== Naming conventions

* *All code variables & functions:* `camelCase`
* *C{plus}{plus} classes, types, & files:* `PascalCase` (e.g., `MyClass.cc`)
* *Executables & directories:* `kebab-case` (e.g., `run-test/`)
* *Environment variables:* `ALL_CAPS_SNAKE_CASE` prefixed with `IMPORTIZER_` (e.g., `IMPORTIZER_OS`)

=== C{plus}{plus} rules

==== Style

* Follow the LLVM coding style.
* Use `std::string_view` over `const char*`, and `std::array`/`std::vector` over C-style arrays.
* Use angled brackets (`#include <header.h>`) for external/third-party headers.
* The C{plus}{plus} file containing `main()` for any executable must be named `Driver.cc`.
* Maintain the exact same ordering of options in the Options section and parsing logic in `getOpts`.

==== Error handling (without Exceptions)

* *Return Values:* Mark fallible functions with `[nodiscard]` and return `bool` (or a type
implicitly convertible to `bool`).
* *Logging:* Functions must handle logging their own errors and should be marked `noexcept`.
* *System Errors:* Mark branches handling system-level errors (e.g., `fseek` or `ftell` failures)
with `[unlikely]`. Do not use this for input validation.
* *Early Exits:* For an errorless early exit (e.g., the user requested `--help` or `--version`),
return `std::optional<bool>` with `std::nullopt` to signal to the caller that execution should halt
successfully without an error code.

=== CMake rules

* Always place `common-config` as the *first* item in your `target_link_libraries` list.
* Only use generator expressions for build-time conditionals (e.g., `<$COMPILE_LANGUAGE:CXX>`).
* Check before adding a compiler/linker flag if it's not guaranteed to be available on supported
compiler (e.g., `-fsanitize=address`).
* `3rd-party` directory must only contain 3rd-party libraries used by the project
* Use `target\_*_*` to add flags for this project, and `add\_*_*` to add for this and all
dependencies. Note https://gitlab.kitware.com/cmake/cmake/-/work_items/27854[this issue].

=== Script rules
* Use CMake to write scripts, if not possible, then make a folder and add scripts for all
supported OS'es (like `setup-env`).
* Environment setup scripts define these environment variables so you can use in other places:
** `IMPORTIZER_OS`: The operating system (`windows`, `linux`, or `macos`)
** `IMPORTIZER_ARCH`: The architecture (`x64` or `arm64`)

=== Checklists

==== New release

. Update importizer's version string in:
** `.github/workflows/Release.yml`
** `ChangeLog.asc`
(delete "in progress")
** `src/importizer/Opts.cc`
** `CMakeLists.txt`

. Run the Tag Release workflow, it will:
** Check if the last commit built and tested successfully (in Debug mode).
** Check if LibTooling binaries are
** Build and test on its own (in Release mode).
** Tag the new release.

==== Bumping LibTooling version

. Tag a new release with (replace `{v}` with the new version):
** Title: `libtooling-{v}`
** Tag: `libtooling-{v}`
** Description: `LibTooling {v} for developers and CI.`
** Pre-release
. Update the version string & LLVM Project hash in `scripts/EnsureLibtooling.cmake`
. Commit with message `Bump LibTooling to {v}`, push, and let the CI run
. Once CI finish, update the LibTooling hashes in `scripts/EnsureLibtooling.cmake`

==== Permissions

When pushing, ensure permission of files in `scripts/` is set to executable. You can use the
provided git hook to do this for you:
[source,bash]
----
git config core.hooksPath .githooks
----
